{
  "texts": [
    "The most impacted tests were aPTT, INR/PT, albumin, BUN, serum calcium, chloride, and CRP.",
    "The removal of weekly panels had a moderate effect (-18%).",
    "Regarding post-cardiac surgery panels, the effect was moderate on creatine kinase isoenzyme MB (-10%) but significant on cardiac troponin (-50%).",
    "Finally, the study showed interesting results on ABG stewardship: potassium and glucose were performed in 90% of cases; pH, PO 2, PCO 2, hemoglobin and sodium were ordered in only 70-80% of analyses; chloride, ionized calcium and lactate were prescribed in only 30-40% of all ABGs.Gatekeeping can also take the form of a self-imposed limitation set by the clinicians themselves.",
    "In a 191-patient study, Sugarman et al. [71] evaluated the adherence to a local standard on seven commonly performed tests (CRP, BUN and electrolytes, serum magnesium, phosphate, liver function tests (LFT), coagulation [not otherwise specified] and FBC), with a self-imposed limit of maximum 25% inappropriate tests."
  ]
}